---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---
<Layout title="Start Here">
  <div class="page-head">
    <span class="eyebrow">Orientation</span>
    <h1>Start here</h1>
    <p class="standfirst">
      What Econschool is, and a sensible path through it — whether your exam is a
      year away or next month.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2>What this is</h2>
  <p>
    Econschool is a learning resource for students preparing for graduate study in
    economics — MA and PhD entrance examinations such as ISI, and comparable
    international programs. It is built around one belief: that serious preparation
    means mathematical rigor, full working, and honest practice — not shortcuts.
  </p>
  <p>
    Most of the site is free: the <a href="https://www.youtube.com/@econ.school">lectures
    on YouTube</a>, the <a href="/problems/">problem library</a>, and the
    <a href="/resources/">resources</a>. The <a href="/prep/">prep program</a> and
    <a href="/workshops/">workshops</a> are paid, live, and small.
  </p>

  <h2>A sensible path</h2>
  <ol>
    <li>
      <strong>Learn from the lectures.</strong> The YouTube channel covers
      microeconomics and the mathematics it rests on, in full detail.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Solve, with your own hands.</strong> Pick problems from the
      <a href="/problems/">library</a>. Attempt every exercise unaided before reading
      any solution — the struggle is where the learning is.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Check your working line by line.</strong> Solved problems here show
      every step precisely so you can find where your attempt diverged.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Go deeper when ready.</strong> The research-to-problem series turns
      major papers into problems you can actually solve — a preview of what graduate
      study feels like.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Get structure if you want it.</strong> If you would rather follow a
      syllabus with live teaching and feedback, that is what the
      <a href="/prep/">prep program</a> is for.
    </li>
  </ol>

  <h2>How to read this site</h2>
  <p>
    Color is notation here, as in all Econschool materials: in every diagram, blue
    is person 1, red is person 2, green marks Pareto-efficient sets, and orange
    marks equilibria and endowments. Once you know the convention, you can read a
    new diagram at a glance.
  </p>
  <p>
    Mathematics is set properly throughout. If a step looks compressed, it isn't —
    every solved problem shows the full working.
  </p>

  <h2>Stay in the loop</h2>
  <p>
    Course dates, new problems, and new videos are posted under
    <a href="/announcements/">News</a>. That page is the single place to check.
  </p>
</Layout>
